  _legacyStoryId: story_zombie_normal
  storySegments:
  - storyId: story_zombie_monk_seg1
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 994ff2491387a4344ba6b17f3f826e0e, type: 2}
    storySummary: "The staff was less a weapon than a battered door bolt, its copper
      ring worn dull yet still warm to the touch. When it returned to his hand, the
      rotund zombie monk seemed pulled upright by an old vow\u2014still shuffling,
      but no longer aimless, his movements set with purpose. Memories flickered:
      in the first days of the apocalypse, refugees crushed against the temple gates,
      supplies ran thin, and the doors began to fail. He cursed, \u201CDon\u2019t
      break my threshold,\u201D and braced the staff across the entrance, driving
      back rioters and infected alike, even hauling water, grain, and wounded like
      a carrying pole. Asked why he held the line, he only said, \u201CMy vows are
      imperfect\u2014but this threshold, I keep pure.\u201D"
  - storyId: story_zombie_monk_seg2
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 5db1e7d6b2c9e3a40a249be3055aec67, type: 2}
    storySummary: "When the prayer beads returned to the corpulent monk-zombie\u2019s
      palm, he stopped at once, a low murmur\u2014almost a sigh\u2014slipping from
      his throat. His past came into focus: before the apocalypse he was a gluttonous,
      hard-drinking monk who joked and haggled, yet each night he sat alone before
      the Buddha, turning the beads to guide souls \u201Cleft without rest\u201D\u2014plague-dead,
      famine-struck, disaster-taken, strangers with no one to mourn them. After the
      world fell, he kept chanting for the infected, beads biting into his wrist
      as he cursed his fate and tried to send them onward. When infection finally
      claimed him, he attempted the same mercy for himself\u2014but the beads could
      not let him go."
  dialogueConversationTitle: ZombieMonk
  shortDescription: "After the apocalypse, a strange legend spread through the ruins:
    a monk as round as a small hill, swaying as he walked, chanting sutras with the
    stink of alcohol and dried meat at his waist. Some called him a fraud who once
    lived off rituals and offerings; others swore he had saved people, though few
    wanted to admit a vow-breaking monk could be compassionate. Now he was no longer
    human\u2014still smiling faintly, eyes hollow as a dried well\u2014and instead
    of hunting the living, he only wandered and reached for the empty space on his
    chest, as if something precious was missing."
